					<h2><a href="http://www.jejik.com/articles/2008/12/sugarcrm_many-to-one_relations_to_standard_modules/">SugarCRM many-to-one relations to standard modules</a></h2>
			<address class="vcard">by <a href="http://www.jejik.com/authors/sander_marechal/" class="url fn">Sander Marechal</a></address>
			<p>The module builder in SugarCRM allows you to create one-to-many relations between one of your custom built modules and a standard module. However, it does not allow you to create many-to-one relationships. This means that it is not possible to create an Invoices module for example, where one account relates to many invoices, but each invoice only relates to one account. While you can create such a relationship by using the &ldquo;Relate&rdquo; field, you will not get a subpanel on the Accounts module that shows all the invoices that relate to in.</p>

<p>In this article I will show you how you can create a many-to-one relation between your custom module and a standard module. This relationship works the same way as the one-to-many relationship with full support for searching and subpanels, only the other way around. My setup is based on my previous two SugarCRM articles: &ldquo;<a href="http://www.jejik.com/articles/2008/12/keeping_sugarcrm_under_subversion_control/">Keeping SugarCRM under Subversion control</a>&rdquo; and &ldquo;<a href="http://www.jejik.com/articles/2008/12/build_custom_sugarcrm_modules_in_subversion/">Build custom SugarCRM modules in Subversion</a>&rdquo;. That means that I will be working inside the installable zip package that is generated by the SugarCRM module builder.</p>

<p>You can <a href="/files/sugarcrm/invoicing-accounts.zip">download the full invoicing package</a> that I created in this article. It has been tested on SugarCRM 5.1.0b.</p>				<div class="postinfo">
