					<h2><a href="http://www.jejik.com/articles/2008/08/the_sugarcrm_cache_directory_demystified/">The SugarCRM cache directory demystified</a></h2>
			<address class="vcard">by <a href="http://www.jejik.com/authors/sander_marechal/" class="url fn">Sander Marechal</a></address>
			<p><strong>Updated 2009-01-07.</strong> One of the projects I am working on at the moment at my day job is customizing <a href="http://www.sugarcrm.com">SugarCRM</a>. We want to start managing all changes to SugarCRM using subversion, so we need to know which bits should be under version control and which bits should not. During my analysis I came across the <a href="http://www.sugardev.net/content/the_pitifully_named_cache_directory">ill&#8208;named and infamous cache directory</a>.</p>

<p>SugarCRM&#8217;s cache is anything but that. I already knew that uploaded files and e-mails were also stored in the cache directory, but I needed to know <em>exactly</em> what was in the cache so I can make some informed decision on what to put under version control and what bits of a production system should be backed up. I found my answer, after a whole lot of <a href="http://www.sugarcrm.com/wiki/index.php?title=Cleaning_Out_Old_Data_and_Files">searching</a>, reading the SugarCRM source code and <a href="http://www.sugarcrm.com/forums/showthread.php?t=36657">asking around</a>. It turns out that the cache directory contains a hodgepodge of user data files, configuration files and&mdash;oh yes, there are some real cache files in there as well.</p>

<p>If there is one thing to take away from this article it&#8217;s &ldquo;Don&#8217;t mess with the cache unless you know what you&#8217;re doing&rdquo;. That bears repeating:</p>

<p><em>&ldquo;Don&#8217;t mess with the cache unless you know what you&#8217;re doing&rdquo;</em></p>

<p>With that firmly burned into the back of your eyeballs, here&#8217;s an overview what the cache directory contains.</p>				<div class="postinfo">
